  • Introduction

  • References

Introduction¶

In this project, we will analyze the data set associated with The Movie Database (TMDB). This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDB), including user ratings and revenue. In particular, we will be interrested in finding the trends affect the revenue of the movies and how differet factor affect the maximization of this revenue with respect to the budget. Also, different visualization will be introduced to emphasize the findings and relations affects the revenue of the movies. This project trys to answer the following questions:

  • Question 1 (Which genres are most frequently seen from year to year?)
  • Question 2 (What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?)
  • Question 3 (What is the total revenue in each year ?)
  • Question 4 (Explain the relation between the total budget and the total revenue in each year ?)
  • Question 5 (Explain the relation between the total budget and the total revenue according to movie title ?)
  • Question 6 (Is there a relation between the director name and the total revenue? Explain?)
  • Question 7 (Explain the relation between the total budget and the total revenue according to vote count and vote average?)

The data type of the column release_date need to be adjusted to be datetime type.

It is remarked when trying to convert release_date to datetime type that there is a problem because the year is given by two digits which make a confusion for example 66 is converted to 2066 and not 1966.

So, the following code is proposed to complete the year before converting to timedate to avoid ambiguity

In [157]:
a=(df['release_date'].str[-2:] >= '60') & (df['release_date'].str[-3:-2] == '/')
b=(df['release_date'].str[-2:] < '60') & (df['release_date'].str[-3:-2] == '/')
df.loc[a,'release_date'] = df['release_date'].str[:-2] + '19' + df['release_date'].str[-2:]
df.loc[b,'release_date'] = df['release_date'].str[:-2] + '20' + df['release_date'].str[-2:]
df['release_date']

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

We start the analysis by visualizing the histograms of all variable to get a general view about the frequency of distribtion relative to each variable.

In [168]:
df.hist(figsize=(16,12));

To get an overview of these histograms, it is shown that the popularity and vote count of the majority of movies has lower values, while a small number of movies have higher popularity and vote count. For the budget and revenue, it is shown that the majority of film has lower budget and revenue, while small number of films has high budget and high revenue. It is also remarked that for the release date and release year, the number of movies significantly increase after year 2000. Considering the runtime it is shown that the majority of movies has a duration from 90 to 130 minitues. for the vote average, it is shown that it has a normal distribution where a small number of movies has lower and higher vote average.

It is also important to show the correlation between the variables especially with the target variable, the revenue

In [177]:
def line_plot(dataF,fig_title,x_label,y_label,fs):
    dataF.plot(figsize=(9,7))
    plt.title(fig_title, fontsize=fs)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=fs)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=fs)
    plt.show()
In [178]:
df_rev_year = df.groupby('release_year')[['revenue']].sum()

Conclusions¶

This project introduced an analysis of the dataset associated with The Movie Database (TMDB). The project starts by cleaning the data to put it in the most clean form to get a good exploratory analysis. Some questions are answered to get more insight into the dataset analysis. Some visualization plots are also presented to get more clarifications about the proposed analysis. Although, there are many questions can be proposed and answered, these proposed questions are presented as a sample of questions that add value for the analysis of the dataset. It is found that the effect of budget is very important to gain high revenue. it is remarked also the number of movies has highly increases after the year 2000. It is also remarked that the vote count realy refer to films with high revenue. Although, the data is cleaned to a good extent, the dataset need to be updated and more correct data need to be added. For completing this project, alot of search on the internet are made and a lot of sites are visited. Sample of the visited sites and reference books are presented in Reference section.
